summary: IDK what to put here. SCPs. Secret plans. Movies. Details in post.
title: IDK what to put here. SCPs. Secret plans. Movies. Details in post.
body:
A recently captured humanoid SCP is being cross experimented with SCPs that are alive and hard to contain. She formulates a plan with them. They pass it on to other SCPs during cross tests, who then relay the info to even more SCPs.

They communicate by coming up with codes. Over the course of several weeks, they observe their own prison cells  containment chambers, as well as the agents bringing them food, to learn everything about what’s keeping them locked up and devise strategies, which they then relay to other SCPs they run into during experiments. Every SCP in on it communicates with every other one whenever they can, to find the perfect strategy. 

Then, on one day, half of them breach containment at once. They let all the other SCPs who were in on it out. Instead of fighting, which usually happens during breaches where one SCP lets others out, they’re collaborating. They team up to escape as fast as possible and throw off the Foundation.

Then, once they’ve escaped, they sneak off to a nearby movie theater and watch Captain Marvel.

summary: god i could write an enormous fucking essay on women superheroes in film and how their superpowers are usually represented....
body: god i could write an enormous fucking essay on women superheroes in film and how their superpowers are usually represented. there are at least 4 or 5 examples coming to mind of like a scene where she is like floating and consumed by fire and screaming with rage, and i don’t know why but those scenes always resonate with me the most, and you never see them with male superheroes i don’t think. i don’t know if this is universal or just my experience, but i think watching a woman onscreen scream, and shout her pain and fury and power is incredibly cathartic, and even more so when it’s physically manifested in like fire around her. i think that for me at least, i as a woman have not been allowed to feel the full extent of my anger the way men are, and watching a woman scream with all of her soul, without regard for her face or her looks, it feels powerful in and of itself. i think that if i did that, yelled like that, i would feel the way those scenes look. it’s almost painfully brilliant to watch.
